item.title: Rocca - Schizotrancea [Trance]
item.dc:creator: blakkaz
item.description:
There is a quite a bit of history behind the term EDM.

I was going to write a big essay, but it‚Äôs probably easier to just link a few articles‚Ä¶

  • DJMag - Can We Please Stop Calling All Dance Music Genres EDM?
  • TheFourOhFive - 5 Reasons Why You Shouldn‚Äôt Call It EDM

I will pull out a few quotes though.

In Europe, we class EDM as a sub-genre of dance music.

The term EDM doesn‚Äôt represent just a style of music, a group of artists or a specific sound. It is, in fact, a way to describe the quick, lucrative and global commodification of dance music between 2010 and now. It‚Äôs a way to describe the conversion of DJs into brands ‚Äî complete with complex social media strategies, image consultants and full-time security details ‚Äî and festivals into retail marketplaces where people gather together to be sold things en masse.

EDM artists haven‚Äôt spent years fetishising the origins or founders of their sound ‚Äî because EDM as a genre simply didn‚Äôt exist before 2010.

What fans need to accept is that the term EDM does NOT mean d&b, techno, ambient, deep house or anything else for that matter, to anyone who‚Äôs been into dance music for longer than the last half a decade. It‚Äôs not an umbrella term, it is a way to describe the mutation of a music scene into a marketable product, symbolising a brief moment in time when the corporate world finally stepped on our turf.

EDM as a phrase isn‚Äôt rooted in the music - it‚Äôs rooted in marketing.

Obviously, the stereotype doesn‚Äôt always hold true, but by and large those exposed to long-time fans and artists over a significant period of time will stop calling it EDM after a while, leaving only the newer and more poorly educated listeners in the group.

Terms like ‚Äúelectronic music‚Äù already exist, cross-referenced and backed up by thousands of well-respected and well-written publications and artists across decades and continents. ‚ÄúEDM,‚Äù on the other hand, finds its primary usage in sales pitches, YouTube comments, and poorly-written, uneducated blogs with surface-scratching ‚Äúreporting‚Äù at best.

The culture of electronic music arguably existed initially to provide a safe space for queer black people living in hugely racist, homophobic, and transphobic cities like Chicago and New York, dancing to socially-shunned styles like disco for hours to be with like-minded people and escape from the crushing hatred of ‚Äúnormal‚Äù society for a while. EDM, on the other hand, is an extravagant display of white straight men making money off of white straight people dancing to music played and produced by white straight men. It runs so contrary to the initial nigh-utopian society in which electronic music was incubated that it‚Äôs almost shocking to see the lack of knowledge and understanding the average fan has about not only the start of the initial movement but also how the current state of affairs reflects (or doesn‚Äôt reflect) the thousands of founders‚Äô intents.

As long as Electric Daisy Carnival and Tomorrowworld are still running, the unattractive reality of poorly-informed, drug-addled bros fist-pumping to Dmitri Vegas and Like Mike will continue to exist, and that kind of misguided hedonism is something to which many people irrevocably attach ‚ÄúEDM‚Äù. Until a change in mindset occurs, the term ‚ÄúEDM‚Äù is best avoided.
